%[text] %[text:anchor:T_453a] # Estimate LLC Converter Resonant Tank Parameters
%[text] This script helps you design and tune the parameters of the LLC converter resonant tank. You use the Simulink® Control System Toolbox™ to plot the gain and impedance curves of the LLC converter using the First Harmonic Approximation (FHA).
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_1541] ## Estimate Resonant Tank Parameters
%[text] You estimate the resonant tank parameters of the LLC converter using the FHA based a specified quality factor $Q${"editStyle":"visual"} and inductance ratio$\\;k${"editStyle":"visual"}. The inductance ratio is the ratio of magnetizing inductance $L\_m${"editStyle":"visual"} to series resonant inductance $L\_r${"editStyle":"visual"}. Achieving soft switching to improve efficiency depends on selecting a suitable magnetizing inductance. Higher magnetizing inductance can lead to lower magnetizing current, which can reduce conduction loss due to low reactive current, but it may also result in hard switching. You must maintain a minimum magnetizing current to ensure zero-voltage switching in the primary switches.
%[text] Resonant tank parameters are estimated using the below equations:
%[text] $\\;Q=\\frac{\\sqrt{\\frac{L\_r }{C\_r }}}{R\_{\\textrm{ac}-\\textrm{load}} }${"editStyle":"visual"} ,  $k=\\frac{L\_{m\\;} }{L\_r }${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text]  $f\_{r\\;} =\\frac{1}{2\\pi \\;\\sqrt{\\;L\_r C\_r }}${"editStyle":"visual"},   $f\_{\\textrm{r2}} =\\frac{1}{2\\pi \\;\\sqrt{\\;\\left(L\_r +L\_m \\right)C\_r }}\\;${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text]  $x=\\frac{f\_s }{f\_r }${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $L\_{m-\\max } =\\left(1-\\frac{T\_s -T\_r }{\\left(\\sqrt{\\;K+1}-1\\right)T\_r }\\right)\\left(\\frac{\\left(1+2k\\sqrt{\\;k+1}-k\\right)T\_{\\textrm{dead}} }{16\\left(k+1\\right)f\_r C\_{\\textrm{parasitic}} }\\right)\\;\\textrm{as}\\;\\textrm{given}\\;\\textrm{in}\\;\\textrm{the}\\;\\textrm{reference}\\;\\left\\lbrack 4\\right\\rbrack${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $T\_{\\textrm{dead}\\;} \\ge 16\\;C\_{\\textrm{parasitic}} L\_m f\_s${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $n=\\frac{N\_1 }{N\_2 }${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $R\_{\\textrm{ac}-\\textrm{effective}} =\\frac{8n^2 }{\\pi {\\;}^2 }\\left(\\frac{V\_o^2 }{P\_{\\textrm{load}} }\\right)${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] Where,
%[text] $\\begin{array}{l}\nQ-\\textrm{Quality}\\;\\textrm{factor}\\\\\nk-\\textrm{Inductance}\\;\\textrm{ratio}\\\\\nf\_r -\\textrm{Resonant}\\;\\textrm{frequency}\\\\\nf\_{\\textrm{r2}} -\\textrm{Second}\\;\\textrm{resonant}\\;\\textrm{frequency}\\\\\nf\_s -\\textrm{Switching}\\;\\textrm{frequency}\\\\\nx-\\textrm{Frequency}\\;\\textrm{ratio}\\\\\nL\_m -\\textrm{Magnetizing}\\;\\textrm{inductance}\\\\\nL\_{m-\\max } -\\textrm{Maximum}\\;\\;m\\textrm{agnetizing}\\;\\textrm{inductance}\\\\\nT\_{\\textrm{dead}} -\\textrm{Dead}\\;\\textrm{time}\\\\\nn-\\textrm{Transformer}\\;\\textrm{turns}\\;\\textrm{ratio}\\\\\nR\_{\\textrm{ac}-\\textrm{effective}} -\\textrm{Effective}\\;\\textrm{AC}\\;\\textrm{load}\\;\\textrm{resistance}\n\\end{array}${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_6874] ### Series Resonant Inductance
%[text] You can achieve the series resonant inductance of the LLC converter either by adding an external inductor or by using the leakage inductance of the transformer. By utilizing the transformer's leakage inductance, you can reduce the size and weight of the converter. The transformer has leakage inductance in both the primary and secondary windings. You can distribute the required series resonant inductance between the primary and secondary windings by inductance distribution factor $h${"editStyle":"visual"}. The gain curve of the LLC resonant converter is influenced by this series inductance distribution factor, with each distribution offering different gain characteristics at non-resonant frequencies.
%[text] The series resonant inductance, $L\_r =L\_{\\textrm{lk1}} +n^2 L\_{\\textrm{lk2}}${"editStyle":"visual"}, the value of primary leakage inductance $L\_{\\textrm{lk1}} =hL\_r${"editStyle":"visual"} and secondary leakage inductance $L\_{\\textrm{lk2}} =\\left|\\frac{\\left(1-h\\right)L\_r }{n^2 }\\right|${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_82a0] ## Specify Converter Rating
%[text] This design solution helps you design and analyze the LLC resonant converter to meet your requirements. Input your LLC converter specifications.
LLCSpec.minInputVoltage =  simscape.Value(350,"V"); % Minimum input voltage (V)
LLCSpec.maxInputVoltage =  simscape.Value(400,"V"); % Maximum input voltage (V)
LLCSpec.minOutputVoltage = simscape.Value(300,"V"); % Minimum output voltage (V)
LLCSpec.maxOutputVoltage = simscape.Value(400,"V"); % Maximum output voltage (V)

LLCSpec.ratedOutputPower = simscape.Value(10000,"W"); % Rated power (W)
LLCSpec.resonantFrequency = simscape.Value(100e3,"Hz"); % Resonant frequency (Hz)
LLCSpec.mosfetDrainSourceCapacitance = simscape.Value(200e-12,"F"); % MOSFET parasitic capacitance (F)
LLCSpec.inductanceDistributionFactor = 0.95; % Inductance distribution factor
nominalOutputVoltage = (LLCSpec.minOutputVoltage.value+LLCSpec.maxOutputVoltage.value)/2;
%[text] In this design solution, you can achieve the required frequency range of operation by adjusting the quality factor and inductance ratio. You do this by tuning the resonant tank parameters using gain curves, which you plot for various load conditions, quality factors, and inductance ratios.
%[text] ## Specify Parasitic Parameters
LLCSpec.Rco = 0.02; % Output filter capacitor ESR resistance (Ohm)
LLCSpec.R1 = 1e-4; % Transformer primary resistance (Ohm)
LLCSpec.R2 = 1e-4; % Transformer secondary resistance (Ohm)
LLCSpec.Rcr = 1e-4; % Resonant capacitor resistance (Ohm)
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_6293] ## Plot Gain Curve of the Resonant Tank
%[text] You can estimate the gain curve of the LLC resonant tank using the Control System Toolbox with a first harmonics approximation. To do this, this design solution use the `GainCurveLLCConverter` model to estimate the resonant tank's gain curve.
%[text] You can plot the gain curves for various quality factors, magnetizing-to-series resonant inductance ratios, and load conditions. These gain curves help you identify suitable operating points for LLC resonant converters. Based on your specifications, you can also plot the minimum and maximum gain required to achieve the desired output voltage range for a given input voltage variation. The gain curve provides the summary of operating frequency with minimum and maximum operating frequency that achieves the required converter gain range.
%[text] To open the model that plots the gain curve, in the command prompt run:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("GainCurveLLCConverter");
%[text] ```
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_3d2a] ### Different DC Load Resistance
%[text] You can estimate the resonant tank parameters based on the given values of the quality factor and inductance ratio. Then, plot the gain curve for various load conditions.  
  %[control:button:084c]{"position":[1,2]}
qualityFactor = 1; % Quality factor
k = 10; % Inductance ratio

outputLoadPU = [0.4 0.6 1]; % DC output load (pu)
Rload = simscape.Value((nominalOutputVoltage^2)./(outputLoadPU*LLCSpec.ratedOutputPower.value),"Ohm"); % Output DC resistance

gainCurve = plotGainCurveLLCConverter(LLCSpec,QualityFactorVec=qualityFactor, ... %[output:group:6af4688e] %[output:50e4bdd3] %[output:3245704e]
    LmLrRatioVec=k,RloadVec=Rload); %#ok<*NASGU> %[output:group:6af4688e] %[output:50e4bdd3] %[output:3245704e]
%[text] To ensure the required output voltage is maintained for any input voltage variation, the gain curves should cover the entire desired gain range across all possible load conditions. If the resonant tank parameters do not satisfy the specified performance criteria, you can adjust the quality factor and the inductance ratio to tune the system accordingly.
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_4efc] ### Different Quality Factor
%[text] To achieve the required gain and operating frequency range, you can plot the gain curve for various quality factors with a given inductance ratio and load conditions. By observing the operating frequency range for different quality factors, you can select the most appropriate quality factor for your application.
  %[control:button:57bd]{"position":[1,2]}
qualityFactor = [0.3 0.7 2]; % Quality factor
k = 7; % Inductance ratio
Rload = simscape.Value((nominalOutputVoltage^2)./(LLCSpec.ratedOutputPower.value),"Ohm");
gainCurve = plotGainCurveLLCConverter(LLCSpec,QualityFactorVec=qualityFactor, ... %[output:group:37716750] %[output:867053e3] %[output:23cd996f]
    LmLrRatioVec=k,RloadVec=Rload); %[output:group:37716750] %[output:867053e3] %[output:23cd996f]
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_7667] ### Different Inductance Ratio
%[text] To further improve the required gain and operating range, you can use the suitable quality factor identified from your previous observation. In this step, you can vary the ratio of magnetizing to resonant inductance for a particular load resistance. By analyzing the gain curve, you can then select the most appropriate inductance ratio.
  %[control:button:6400]{"position":[1,2]}
qualityFactor = 0.5; % Quality factor
k = [5 8 12]; % Inductance ratio vector
Rload = simscape.Value((nominalOutputVoltage^2)/LLCSpec.ratedOutputPower.value,"Ohm");
gainCurve = plotGainCurveLLCConverter(LLCSpec,QualityFactorVec=qualityFactor, ... %[output:group:2b29eea9] %[output:4aca238e] %[output:266f1df6]
    LmLrRatioVec=k,RloadVec=Rload); %[output:group:2b29eea9] %[output:4aca238e] %[output:266f1df6]
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_89d4] ## The Selected Resonant Tank Parameters
%[text] For the given quality factor and inductance ratio, you can estimate the LLC converter resonant tank parameters that meet your requirements, use the `designLLCConverter` function.
  %[control:button:3672]{"position":[1,2]}
LLCSpec.qualityFactor = 0.5; % Quality factor
LLCSpec.k = 5; % Inductance ratio
Rload = simscape.Value((nominalOutputVoltage^2)./(LLCSpec.ratedOutputPower.value),"Ohm");
[~, Frequency, frequencyRange] = plotGainCurveLLCConverter(LLCSpec,QualityFactorVec=LLCSpec.qualityFactor, ... %[output:group:85bf285c] %[output:8d1a9b6a] %[output:2db04d98]
    LmLrRatioVec=LLCSpec.k,RloadVec=Rload); %[output:group:85bf285c] %[output:8d1a9b6a] %[output:2db04d98]
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_500a] ## Estimate LLC Converter Parameters
%[text] Based on your given specifications, quality factor, and inductance ratio, you can use the `designLLCConverter` MATLAB® function  to estimate the LLC converter parameters that meet your requirements.
[designTable, LLCDesign]  = designLLCFullBridgeConverter(LLCSpec); % Estimate LLC converter parameters %[output:264d1021]
%[text] 
%[text] Verify that the selected parameters provide soft switching over the required frequency range. You can use the `estimateMaximumMagInductance` function to determine the maximum magnetizing inductance required for soft switching operation in the discontinuous conduction region. The chosen magnetizing inductance should be less than the estimated maximum value both near and far from the resonant frequency.
SwitchingFrequency = simscape.Value(60e3,"Hz");
magL = estimateMaximumMagInductance(LLCDesign,SwitchingFrequency=SwitchingFrequency,DisplayTableFlag=true); %[output:49f5b8ae]
%%
%[text] ## Plot the Impedance Curve
%[text] You can plot the impedance curve of the resonant tank in the low-frequency capacitive region and the high-frequency inductive region.
  %[control:button:9810]{"position":[1,2]}
outputLoadPU = [0.4 0.6 1]; % DC output load (pu) at which impedance curve is plotted
Rload = simscape.Value((nominalOutputVoltage^2)./(outputLoadPU*LLCSpec.ratedOutputPower.value),"Ohm"); % Output DC resistance

[magnitude, frequency] = plotLLCResonantTankImpedanceCurve(LLCDesign,RloadVec=Rload); %[output:7e2f4d16]
%%
